description:
Current Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) significantly improve performance by generating long-chain reasoning, but also introduce serious problems of redundant reasoning and structural disorder. Existing methods (such as Self-Braking Tuning) mainly optimize from the perspective of "length control" or "posterior pruning," lacking global constraints on the reasoning structure itself.  
 &nbsp; 
  This paper proposes a novel training paradigm: Matroid-Governed Reasoning (MGR). This method introduces the independence structure from Matroid Theory into the modeling of the reasoning process for the first time, treating the "set of reasoning steps" as a combinatorial structure satisfying the independence axiom, and defining the "optimal reasoning path" as a maximal independent set (basis). Under this framework, reasoning is no longer linearly generated, but a combinatorial selection process constrained by structure.  
 &nbsp; 
  We propose:  
 &nbsp; 
  A Matroid modeling method for reasoning trajectories (Reasoning Matroid)  
 &nbsp; 
  An exchange-based reasoning refinement mechanism (Exchange-based Reasoning Refinement)  
 &nbsp; 
  A Greedy-Optimal Learning Objective (Greedy-Optimal Learning Objective)  
 &nbsp; 
  Basis Consistency Regularization  
 &nbsp; 
  This paradigm fundamentally changes the way LRMs are trained: shifting from "generating more" to "selecting the optimal structure." Theoretically, it is proven that this method can minimize redundancy while ensuring reasoning completeness and naturally avoid overthinking problems.

